## Why Lab Grown Round Diamonds Are the Highest-Value Diamond Purchase in {{year}}

I am **Farzana Hasan**, GIA-certified diamond expert. The lab-grown diamond market has gone from industry curiosity to mainstream purchase option in under a decade. In {{year}}, approximately 20–25% of all engagement ring center stones sold in the US are lab-grown. That number was under 5% in 2020.

The reason for the growth is obvious: **the price gap is enormous.**

A natural round brilliant at GIA Excellent cut, G color, VS1 clarity, 1.00ct costs $3,200–$3,840 on Blue Nile. The lab-grown equivalent at D-IF Ideal — a significantly better specification — costs $1,560. If you do not care about natural origin, this is one of the most dramatic value propositions in luxury goods.

But lab-grown diamonds are not a simple upgrade over natural that every buyer should make without thinking. There are real trade-offs, real risks in the purchase process, and a resale reality that many lab diamond guides gloss over. This guide covers all of it.

For the technical foundation on round brilliant cut quality — the proportions and grades that apply equally to lab and natural rounds — read the [round cut diamond guide](/round-cut-diamond). For the complete natural vs lab price comparison across all specs, see the [lab grown vs natural diamond price guide](/lab-grown-vs-natural-diamond-price).

