## The Lab Price Floor Effect: Why Waiting Is No Longer a Strategy

From 2019 to 2024, lab-grown diamond prices fell dramatically — in some categories, 60–70% over five years. Buyers who purchased a 1ct D-IF lab round in 2021 at $4,000 watched the same spec drop to $2,000 by 2023 and $1,560 by {{year}}. This created a rational investor mentality: wait for further price drops before buying.

That strategy made sense through 2024. It no longer does.

Lab diamond prices stabilized in late 2025 for a structural reason: the cost efficiency of CVD (Chemical Vapor Deposition) growth has reached near-optimal levels for current technology. The major producers — primarily in India, China, and the US — are operating at low margins on standard round brilliant production. Further price reductions require either a technological leap in growth efficiency or a sustained oversupply scenario that current industry consolidation is working against.

The floor may still have minor room to move — a 5–10% further decline is possible over the next 12–18 months as inventory cycles through. But the 40–60% annual price drops are over. If you are waiting to save 20% more, the wait time would likely be 3–5 years and is not worth it for a purchase you want to enjoy now.

