## What Specs Should You Buy in a Lab Grown Round Diamond?

The same rules as natural — but the economics shift the optimal choice significantly.

With natural diamonds, the typical recommendation is G–H color and VS1–VS2 clarity because these grades are indistinguishable from better grades in normal wear while being substantially cheaper.

With lab-grown diamonds, the price gap between grades is much smaller. A lab D-IF at $1,560 vs a lab G-VS1 at approximately $850–$1,000 — a $560–$710 difference. At those absolute dollar amounts, the case for buying the "budget tier" lab is weaker. You can get dramatically better specifications for less money than you would pay for a good natural diamond.

My lab round buying framework for {{year}}:

**Under $1,500:** Lab D-IF Ideal at $1,560 is just at this threshold. This single stone offers better specs than any natural diamond under $5,000. It is the clearest value proposition in the diamond market.

**$1,500–$2,500:** Lab E-FL Ideal at $2,380. Flawless clarity and E color — identical to natural equivalents priced at $8,500–$10,000.

**$2,500–$3,500:** Lab D-FL Ideal at $3,330. Flawless clarity and D color — the theoretical peak of diamond quality specification at 65% savings over natural.

**Above $3,500 for lab:** Reconsider whether natural is the better purchase. At $4,000+, a natural G-VS1 Excellent round becomes accessible. If resale value or natural origin matters to the buyer, $4,000 is roughly where natural starts to compete on total value.

